swoman was not unmarried or particularly rebellious, but a woman who reconciled entrepreneurship with her femininity and her identity as a wife, mother, or widow. The entrepreneurial woman was the product of a frontier ethos in British Columbia that translated into higher rates of marriage for women and more married women working outside the home than in any other province in Canada. Like men, they worked to support their families.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBusinesswomenxFamily relationshipszBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aBusinesswomenzBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSelf-employed womenxFamily relationshipszBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aSelf-employed womenzBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzBritish ColumbiaxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077481815540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774818155423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774818155/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles